        title: "What the Research Actually Says",
        content: `The most credible research on AI and employment does not tell a story of mass replacement. It tells a story of significant transformation.
The McKinsey Global Institute estimates that by 2030, up to 30 percent of hours worked globally could be automated. That sounds alarming until you read the context: the same research suggests that automation will create demand for new roles, shift the nature of existing ones and increase productivity in ways that expand economic output rather than simply contracting headcount.
The World Economic Forum's Future of Jobs report tells a similar story. Yes, millions of roles will be displaced. But millions of new roles will be created — in AI oversight, data analysis, human-AI collaboration management and the kind of complex, creative, relationship-driven work that AI cannot replicate.
The historical parallel is instructive. The introduction of spreadsheet software in the 1980s was predicted to decimate accounting jobs. Instead, the number of accountants grew — because spreadsheets made accounting faster and cheaper, expanding the market for accounting services and freeing accountants to do higher-value work. ATMs were predicted to eliminate bank tellers. The number of bank tellers increased — because ATMs reduced the cost of running a bank branch, enabling banks to open more branches and offer more services.
AI will follow a similar pattern in many sectors. Not elimination — transformation.`
