        title: "What Business Leaders Should Do Now",
        content: `The businesses that navigate this transition well are not the ones that ignore it or the ones that panic about it. They are the ones that engage with it honestly and proactively.
Have the conversation before the rumours start. When teams do not have information, they fill the gap with anxiety. Tell your team what AI means for the business, what it means for their specific roles, and what the plan is. Honest communication — even when the honest answer is "some things will change and we are still figuring out the details" — is better than silence.
Involve your team in identifying automation opportunities. The people doing the work know better than anyone else which parts of their jobs are tedious, repetitive and ripe for automation. Involving them in that process transforms AI from something being done to them into something they are shaping. That difference in framing changes everything about how adoption lands.
Invest in reskilling alongside automation. When a process is automated, the person who previously performed it needs somewhere to go. That might be a higher-value version of their existing role. It might be a new role in managing the automation. In some cases it might be a different role entirely. Businesses that plan for this transition — rather than leaving it to chance — retain better people, avoid painful redundancy situations and build internal goodwill around AI adoption.
Distinguish between roles and tasks. The temptation is to think about AI in terms of which jobs it will replace. The more useful frame is which tasks within each job it will handle. Almost no role is defined by a single task type. Breaking roles down into their component tasks and asking which can be automated, which will be augmented and which remain fully human gives a much more accurate picture of what will actually change.
Set the tone from the top. In businesses where leaders are openly curious about AI, willing to experiment and transparent about what they are learning, teams follow. In businesses where leaders are anxious or dismissive, teams are too. The cultural tone around AI adoption is set by how leadership engages with it publicly.`
